Among crypto skeptics, one particularly popular thing to be skeptical=C2=A0=
about=C2=A0is Tether, the biggest stablecoin. One Tether is supposed to be =
worth $1, because each Tether =E2=80=94=C2=A0there are about 66 billion Tet=
hers outstanding =E2=80=94=C2=A0is supposed to be backed by $1 of safe doll=
ar-denominated assets. A lot of people believe that Tether is not in fact f=
ully backed, for reasons like =E2=80=9Cit definitely was not fully backed a=
t all points in the past,   in really sketchy ways,=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9Ci=
t   continues to   seem really sketchy,=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9Cit keeps  pro=
mising to do audits and then not doing them,=E2=80=9D and, I mean, there=E2=
=80=99s a lot. And Tether seems to be central to  the workings of the crypt=
o financial system; if your basic thesis is =E2=80=9Ccrypto is a house of c=
ards=E2=80=9D then you might well think that Tether is part of what is prop=
ping it up.
If you think things like this, one thing that you might want to do is bet a=
gainst cryptocurrencies by selling them short. And betting against Tether s=
eems particularly attractive, for two reasons:
=09Tether just kind of makes people mad in ways that other cryptocurrencies=
 don=E2=80=99t.=09A key feature of Tether is that it=C2=A0can=E2=80=99t go =
up. If you think Bitcoin will go to zero, so you short Bitcoin at $17,000, =
and you are wrong and Bitcoin goes to $67,000, you have lost $50,000, oops.=
 But if you think Tether will go to zero, so you short Tether at $1, Tether=
 will not go to $2.=C2=A0If you are wrong, Tether will stay at $1: If Tethe=
r works perfectly, then it will be a successful stablecoin and always worth=
 a dollar. If you bet against it and you=E2=80=99re wrong, you won=E2=80=99=
t lose money. I mean, you=E2=80=99ll pay some funding cost on your bet, but=
 the bet can=E2=80=99t really move=C2=A0against=C2=A0you. There is asymmetr=
ic upside.

This is obvious stuff and people keep noticing and wanting to bet against T=
ether, and then often they think about it for a bit and change their minds.=
 Bloomberg=E2=80=99s  Annie Massa and Katherine Burton report:

A handful of hedge funds are now turning their focus back to the $66 billio=
n stablecoin, which they warn could be the next crypto catastrophe =E2=80=
=94 one that would make the implosion of Bankman-Fried=E2=80=99s FTX exchan=
ge look small in comparison.=C2=A0
