<table class=3D"header" width=3D"100%" border=3D"0" cellspacing=3D"0" cellp=
adding=3D"0">
<tr>
<td class=3D"body-header-container" style=3D"border-collapse: collapse; mso=
-table-lspace: 0pt; mso-table-rspace: 0pt;">
<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Stock snipers</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Look, if someone on Twitter or Discord says th=
at he is an expert day trader who has made millions trading penny stocks an=
d will teach you his secrets, then I can tell you his secret. Here it is:</=
p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">He buys penny stocks.</li>=09<li styl=
e=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Then he goes on Twitter and Discord and tells <em=
>you=C2=A0</em>to buy them because they are so good and will go up.</li>=09=
<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">You =E2=80=94=C2=A0and his other Twitter =
followers =E2=80=94 buy them, which makes them go up.</li>=09<li style=3D"m=
argin-bottom: 5px;">He sells them to you at a profit.</li>=09<li style=3D"m=
argin-bottom: 5px;">Then you are stuck with them. They are not in fact good=
 =E2=80=94=C2=A0they just went up because he told you to buy them =E2=80=94=
 and you end up selling them at a loss.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: =
5px;">He posts pictures of himself standing next to Ferraris, to validate h=
is multimillionaire-day-trader status.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5=
px;">Other people see the Ferraris=C2=A0and want to get into the game.</li>=
=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">He repeats this process.</li>=09<li st=
yle=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">In the fullness of time, the US Securities and =
Exchange Commission and federal prosecutors notice.</li>=09<li style=3D"mar=
gin-bottom: 5px;">They go find his chats and emails and maybe surreptitious=
ly record some of his private conversations.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bot=
tom: 5px;">In all of those chats he turns out to have said things like =E2=
=80=9CI love doing crime=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9Clook at me doing all these c=
rimes=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9Cthis stuff I am doing is market manipulation, a=
 crime=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9Ccrime crime crime crime crime crime,=E2=80=9D =
but with more swearing.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">The prosec=
utors and SEC bring fraud charges.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;"=
>In a sense, the complaints are very boring, because this is the most obvio=
us sort of financial crime, and every case is exactly the same.</li>=09<li =
style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">In another sense, the complaints are entertai=
ning, because of the chats.</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This is called a =E2=80=9Cpump-and-dump.=E2=80=
=9D I don=E2=80=99t know why people keep falling for it? I guess the pictur=
es of the Ferraris. Also a desire for investing to be <em>easy</em>, for it=
 to be a=C2=A0<em>trick=C2=A0</em>that you can learn from some clever insid=
ers on a Discord. If I tell you =E2=80=9Cbuying stock is about allocating c=
apital to productive businesses and sharing, over the long term, in the val=
ue they create for society,=E2=80=9D and some guy standing next to a Ferrar=
i on Twitter says =E2=80=9Cbuying stocks is about interpreting mysterious s=
ignals that tell you THIS STOCK WILL GO UP 200% THIS AFTERNOON,=E2=80=9D hi=
s theory sounds more fun, and it certainly sounds like it will make you mor=
e money more quickly than my theory. It=C2=A0<em>will=C2=A0</em>make=C2=A0<=
em>him=C2=A0</em>more money more quickly. Like, the guy=C2=A0<em>is=C2=A0</=
em>a successful day trader. It=E2=80=99s just that his secret is tricking y=
ou.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I say =E2=80=9Cyou,=E2=80=9D but I doubt anyon=
e reading this column is actually getting tricked. This whole online subcul=
ture =E2=80=94=C2=A0people who go on Twitter and Discord so they can be tri=
cked by pump-and-dump scammers =E2=80=94=C2=A0is quite large and very hard =
for me to understand. My assumption is that a lot of them think they are wi=
se to the scam. If some pump-and-dump scammer pumps a stock, and you buy it=
 a second after he pumps it and sell it a second before he dumps it, you ca=
n make money alongside him. You are knowingly playing hot potato; you are t=
rying to follow his lead to take advantage of his=C2=A0<em>other=C2=A0</em>=
victims. Perhaps this will work, or perhaps it won=E2=80=99t and you=E2=80=
=99ll end up a victim too, but maybe it beats having a real job.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"><a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness=
.com/click/29982587.260529/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9uZXdzL3ByZXNzLXJlbGVh=
c2UvMjAyMi0yMjE/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB485f6784" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" i=
temscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-deco=
ration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #00=
0000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">Anyway</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The Securities and Exchange Commission today a=
nnounced charges against eight individuals in a $100 million securities fra=
ud scheme in which they used the social media platforms Twitter and Discord=
 to manipulate exchange-traded stocks.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">According to the SEC, since at least January 2=
020, seven of the defendants promoted themselves as successful traders and =
cultivated hundreds of thousands of followers on Twitter and in stock tradi=
ng chatrooms on Discord. These seven defendants allegedly purchased certain=
 stocks and then encouraged their substantial social media following to buy=
 those selected stocks by posting price targets or indicating they were buy=
ing, holding, or adding to their stock positions. However, as the complaint=
 alleges, when share prices and/or trading volumes rose in the promoted sec=
urities, the individuals regularly sold their shares without ever having di=
sclosed their plans to dump the securities while they were promoting them.<=
/p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">"As our complaint states, the defendants used =
social media to amass a large following of novice investors and then took a=
dvantage of their followers by repeatedly feeding them a steady diet of mis=
information, which resulted in fraudulent profits of approximately $100 mil=
lion," said Joseph Sansone, Chief of the SEC Enforcement Division=E2=80=99s=
 Market Abuse Unit. "Today=E2=80=99s action exposes the true motivation of =
these alleged fraudsters and serves as another warning that investors shoul=
d be wary of unsolicited advice they encounter online."</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">There are also <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bl=
oombergbusiness.com/click/29982587.260529/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuanVzdGljZS5nb3Yvb=
3BhL3ByL2VpZ2h0LW1lbi1pbmRpY3RlZC0xMTQtbWlsbGlvbi1zZWN1cml0aWVzLWZyYXVkLXNj=
aGVtZS1vcmNoZXN0cmF0ZWQtdGhyb3VnaC1zb2NpYWwtbWVkaWE/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23=
cB2f440c57" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank=
" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-=
width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backg=
round-color: #ccc;"> federal criminal charges</a> in Texas. The SEC complai=
nt gives each defendant his online nickname, like a Mafia indictment but mu=
ch less intimidating:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">EDWARD CONSTANTIN, a/k/a =E2=80=9C=
MrZackMorris,=E2=80=9D a/k/a =E2=80=9CEdward Constantinescu,=E2=80=9D PERRY=
 MATLOCK, a/k/a =E2=80=9CPJ Matlock,=E2=80=9D THOMAS COOPERMAN, a/k/a =E2=
=80=9CTommy Coops,=E2=80=9D GARY DEEL, a/k/a =E2=80=9CMystic Mac,=E2=80=9D =
MITCHELL HENNESSEY, a/k/a =E2=80=9CHugh Henne,=E2=80=9D STEFAN HRVATIN, a/k=
/a =E2=80=9CLadeBackk,=E2=80=9D DANIEL KNIGHT, a/k/a =E2=80=9CDeity of Dips=
,=E2=80=9D and JOHN RYBARCYZK, a/k/a =E2=80=9CUltra Calls,=E2=80=9D a/k/a =
=E2=80=9CThe Stock Sniper,=E2=80=9D Defendants.</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">They were on Twitter, they had Discord forums =
called Atlas Trading and Sapphire Trading, they had a podcast:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In July 2020, Knight and Hennessey=
 launched a podcast called =E2=80=9CPennies: Going in Raw=E2=80=9D (=E2=80=
=9CPGIR=E2=80=9D). PGIR bills itself as an informational podcast =E2=80=9C[=
d]iscussing volume, price targets, penny stocks, accumulation, reverse spli=
ts and much more=E2=80=9D and claims to be the =E2=80=9C#1 Stock Market Pod=
cast in America=E2=80=9D with over 2.3 million downloads.=C2=A0</p></blockq=
uote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">They said things in public:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Matlock (@PJ_Matlock): <em>I=E2=80=99ll never =
get sick of pumping.... money into my followers bank accounts. LETS ALL GET=
 RICH!</em></p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Hennessey (@Hugh_Henne): <em>Every single memb=
er of atlas admin Have the same goal... to get as many people away from the=
 9-5 slavery and into the area of financial freedom and f u money. =E2=9D=
=A4 our gains but seeing stories of others paying off debt&amp; banking is =
much more rewarding @MrZackMorris @PJ_Matlock =E2=80=A6</em></p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">On December 19, 2020, Hennessey tweeted: <em>=
=E2=80=9CATLAS has the most self made millionaires We do not even know the =
names of the people that consider us their "competition" We are the '85 Bea=
rs. No one survives.=E2=80=9D</em> =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">On December 29, 2021, Rybarcyzk tweeted:<em> =
=E2=80=9CI=E2=80=99m trying to hit 777 millionaire traders 2022. I=E2=80=99=
m gonna make it happen. It=E2=80=99s not my goal to only make me prosper. I=
 want all of you to prosper. I=E2=80=99m gonna make each and every one of y=
ou make it. The market is so universal. You just adapt to current condition=
s. Let=E2=80=99s go crazy.=E2=80=9D</em></p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The complaint also includes pictures they twee=
ted of a McLaren, a Ferrari, a Lamborghini, just exactly what you=E2=80=99d=
 expect. Meanwhile, the private chats:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The Defendants sometimes discussed their schem=
e over Discord voice chats that they believed were private, but were being =
recorded. For example, on March 1, 2021, Knight and Cooperman (along with o=
thers) discussed the group=E2=80=99s manipulation of the securities of GTT =
Communications, Inc., which at the time traded on the New York Stock Exchan=
ge (=E2=80=9CNYSE=E2=80=9D) under the ticker GTT.=C2=A0The following is a p=
ortion of the conversation:</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"><em>Knight: </em>Get caught? . . . We=E2=80=99=
re robbing f*cking idiots of their money. . .</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"><em>Cooperman: </em>It=E2=80=99s so funny beca=
use I can see the . . . . I can like see the timeline of these. Like I get =
it [the ticker], I send it to Dan [Knight]. I know Dan=E2=80=99s on voice. =
Dan tells you guys. I see it go up more. Then I send it to Gary [Deel] and =
I see it go up like way more [laughter] . . . . My other thing is too, is l=
ike alright, if we lose on one of these, we=E2=80=99ve won on like a hundre=
d so . . . We gotta remember with these Ultra [Rybarcyzk] ones, they all do=
 the same thing. It like spikes, comes down for a second=E2=80=94</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"><em>Knight: </em>Then the scalpers get out, li=
ke Gary [Deel] gets out, then=E2=80=94</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"><em>Cooperman:</em> And then it goes f*cking b=
ukoo, but no, that=E2=80=99s not only it. Like what he [Rybarcyzk] does is =
he alerts it, and then like five minutes later, all his little minions star=
t like retweeting it and saying added with him, so it like builds the hype =
back up. It happens every single time. They have their shit down to a f*cki=
ng science, it=E2=80=99s crazy.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And here=E2=80=99s a guy who almost got it:</p=
>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In another surreptitiously recorded Discord ca=
ll, on February 24, 2021, involving Knight, Cooperman, and others, Knight a=
cknowledged that he understood the Primary Defendants were engaging in mark=
et manipulation, and explained why he posted fewer recommendations on Twitt=
er and Atlas than the Primary Defendants:</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9C[The less] I mention a stock, the les=
s likely I get involved whenever all of Atlas gets a class action f*cking l=
awsuit . . . I=E2=80=99m playing this extremely smart, for the very long te=
rm. If you don=E2=80=99t think all these f*ckers go to jail or at least get=
 sued, you are crazy. . . playing stupid does not work in court. . . it=E2=
=80=99s market manipulation. . . . I mean you look up the definition of mar=
ket manipulation . . .=E2=80=9D</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">There are, I think, roughly two ways to do thi=
s sort of pump-and-dump:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">You say =E2=80=9Cthis company has fou=
nd a cure for cancer so its stock will go up,=E2=80=9D and then you dump th=
e stock. Or,</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">You say =E2=80=9Cthis=
 company=E2=80=99s stock will go up,=E2=80=9D and then you dump the stock.=
=C2=A0</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">There is a subtle difference. The first approa=
ch imitates, in some rough way, real stock analysis. You say things about t=
he underlying business and its potential cash flows; you make the case that=
 the stock will go up for fundamental reasons. Presumably you are lying, bu=
t you are lying about=C2=A0<em>the company</em>. Your goal is to trick peop=
le into thinking the stock is a good investment.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The second approach is pure nihilism; it=E2=80=
=99s just =E2=80=9Cnever mind cash flows, I have some ability to pick the s=
tocks that will go up and I have picked this one.=E2=80=9D You=E2=80=99re n=
ot even lying, really. You <em>do </em>have the ability to pick stocks that=
 go up: By picking a penny stock and telling your Twitter followers to buy =
it, you make the stock go up. Your Twitter followers are not buying the sto=
ck because they think it has a cure for cancer; they are buying it because =
they think that stock investing is an arbitrary game that you have figured =
out, or possibly because they know you=E2=80=99re doing a pump-and-dump but=
 they hope to get out in time. Or possibly those are the same thing. In any=
 case, the game is pretty transparent.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">These guys seem to have done a bit of both. So=
me of their posting was about their own trading, about the meta-game of pum=
ping and dumping:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Matlock (Twitter): <em>And I=E2=80=99m not pum=
ping and dumping on anyone. Why would I sell when I truly believe $RIBT get=
s over $1.50-$2. Haters mad to see anyone winning and come out if the stock=
 is down 3% . All I post is information about it. </em></p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Deel (Twitter): <em>$BCTX recap: I buy stocks =
that I think have a good chart and good news. That=E2=80=99s how I always p=
lay it and sometimes it goes the wrong way. That=E2=80=99s trading. I never=
 dump shares on alerts. BCTX got smacked hard on a vwap reject and I took t=
he L with you guys earlier. On to next</em></p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">On the other hand, there was also some alleged=
 lying about actual companies:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In the course of the scheme, vario=
us Defendants often highlighted an anticipated event that would purportedly=
 raise the stock price (a =E2=80=9Ccatalyst=E2=80=9D) and encouraged buying=
 and holding the stock until the event, falsely claiming that they too were=
 holding the stock waiting for the catalyst. In the case of TRCH, the catal=
yst was a purported upcoming merger with another company, Metamaterial Inc.=
 Hennessey claimed that he had discovered that this merger was coming in th=
e course of his due diligence (=E2=80=9Cdd=E2=80=9D) research on the compan=
y. Hennessey repeatedly promoted false information about Meta itself (e.g.,=
 that it was worth =E2=80=9Cnorth of $4.8 billion=E2=80=9D) and promoted th=
e purported benefits of the merger. Hennessey also posted about other purpo=
rted long-term benefits to TRCH stock holders, including a =E2=80=9Cdividen=
d=E2=80=9D that TRCH shareholders would purportedly receive after the merge=
r. Hennessey also claimed that Meta was potentially partnering with Tesla, =
and that Meta had products that had applications for fighting COVID-19 and =
thus a =E2=80=9C10 billion dollar MARKET CAP POTENTIAL.=E2=80=9D</p></block=
quote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Yeah =E2=80=9Cthis company found a cure for Co=
vid and is also partnering with Tesla=E2=80=9D is pretty straightforward fr=
aud.</p>
