<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If you think things like this, one thing that =
you might want to do is bet against cryptocurrencies by selling them short.=
 And betting against <em>Tether </em>seems particularly attractive, for two=
 reasons:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Tether just kind of makes people mad =
in ways that other cryptocurrencies don=E2=80=99t.</li>=09<li style=3D"marg=
in-bottom: 5px;">A key feature of Tether is that it=C2=A0<em>can=E2=80=99t =
go up</em>. If you think Bitcoin will go to zero, so you short Bitcoin at $=
17,000, and you are wrong and Bitcoin goes to $67,000, you have lost $50,00=
0, oops. But if you think Tether will go to zero, so you short Tether at $1=
, Tether will not go to $2.=C2=A0If you are wrong, Tether will stay at $1: =
If Tether works perfectly, then it will be a successful stablecoin and alwa=
ys worth a dollar. If you bet against it and you=E2=80=99re wrong, you won=
=E2=80=99t lose money. I mean, you=E2=80=99ll pay some funding cost on your=
 bet, but the bet can=E2=80=99t really move=C2=A0<em>against=C2=A0</em>you.=
 There is asymmetric upside.</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This is obvious stuff and people keep noticing=
 and wanting to bet against Tether, and then often they think about it for =
a bit and change their minds. Bloomberg=E2=80=99s <a href=3D"https://link.m=
ail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/29982587.260529/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJ=
