ground-color: #ccc;"> Annie Massa and Katherine Burton report</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">A handful of hedge funds are now turning their=
 focus back to the $66 billion stablecoin, which they warn could be the nex=
t crypto catastrophe =E2=80=94 one that would make the implosion of Bankman=
-Fried=E2=80=99s FTX exchange look small in comparison.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Fir Tree Capital Management and Viceroy Resear=
ch are among the firms shorting Tether, according to people familiar with t=
heir wagers =E2=80=94 positions they=E2=80=99ve held for months, waiting to=
 cash in on their bets.=C2=A0</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The short is hardly straightforward. Valiant, =
a San Francisco-based hedge fund, made the trade earlier this year, but bac=
ked away and made it out unscathed, according to people familiar with the m=
atter. The fund would consider shorting Tether again if it could do so with=
out risking collateral, the people said.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Philippe Laffont=E2=80=99s Coatue Management a=
nd other funds looked at the trade and also passed due to counterparty risk=
, according to people familiar with the matter.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CI=E2=80=99m not short Tether =E2=80=
=93 I haven=E2=80=99t found the vehicle,=E2=80=9D said Andrew Left, founder=
 of Citron Research, a short seller. =E2=80=9CIf someone showed me a way to=
 do it with Goldman Sachs as a counterparty, I=E2=80=99m in.=E2=80=9D</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The problem is that if you want to short Tethe=
r, you have to borrow Tether to sell it. If you want to borrow Tether, you =
will probably have to post collateral: You borrow $100 million of Tether, a=
nd you give your lender back $150 million or $100 million or $50 million of=
 collateral, Treasury bills or Bitcoins or whatever, as security for the Te=
ther loan. You can borrow Tether <em>from Tether=C2=A0</em>=E2=80=94=C2=A0t=
he entity that issues Tethers <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusines=
s.com/click/29982587.260529/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2F=
ydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMTItMDEvc2JmLW1pc3NlZC1mdHgtcy1yaXNrcz9jbXBpZD1CQkQxMjE0Mj=
JfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fd=
GVybT0yMjEyMTQmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBbc5=
978d5" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" sty=
le=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width=
: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background=
-color: #ccc;">  does seem to lend out new Tethers against various sorts of=
 cryptocurrency collateral</a> =E2=80=94=C2=A0or from someone else, some cr=
ypto exchange or crypto hedge fund or lending platform that has a lot of Te=
thers and wants to make some money by lending them.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The problem is that you are posting collateral=
 to your Tether lender, and do you trust them? In the state of the world wh=
ere Tether goes to zero, are you getting your collateral back? From a crypt=
o exchange or crypto hedge fund or crypto lending platform? Or from=C2=A0<e=
m>Tether itself</em>? Tether is widely regarded as being central to the fun=
ctioning of the levered crypto financial system, and a bet against Tether i=
s a bet on the collapse of that system generally. If the system collapses, =
you=E2=80=99re not getting your collateral back.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Or you can bet against Tether by shorting Teth=
er futures on some crypto exchange.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#foo=
tnote-1" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-=
bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none =
!important; background-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block=
;">
<span>[1]</span>
</a>=C2=A0FTX, for instance, offered Tether futures, before it went bankrup=
t last month. You can see the problem here. The problem is that it went ban=
krupt last month. More generally, though, it=E2=80=99s the same as the prob=
lem in the previous paragraph: If Tether goes to zero, the crypto exchange =
where you shorted Tether futures might not still be around to pay out your =
bet.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">So in round numbers the way to make a $100 mil=
lion bet against Tether is (1) you take $100 million of your own money, (2)=
 you park it with some crypto counterparty to borrow 100 million Tethers, (=
3) you sell those Tethers, (4) Tether goes to zero, (5) you buy back the Te=
thers for $0, (6) you go back to your counterparty and say =E2=80=9Chere=E2=
=80=99s my 100 million Tethers, can I have my $100 million back,=E2=80=9D a=
nd (7) your counterparty is just a smoking crater and your $100 million is =
gone. Being short Tether is a lot like being long Tether.</p>
